	<tr><td>old probe, x10<br/><br/>Only slightly worse. Goes into the negative though.</td><td><a href="imgs/RAMP28_5MHz_x10_OldProbe.png"><img width="300px" src="imgs/RAMP28_5MHz_x10_OldProbe.png"/></a></td></tr>
	<tr><td>new probe - old scope, x10<br/><br/>Shows a nice smooth signal.</td><td><a href="imgs/RAMP28_5MHz_x10_OldScope.png"><img width="300px" src="imgs/RAMP28_5MHz_x10_OldScope_small.png"/></a></td></tr>
	</table>
     </desc>
  </section>

  <section toc="summary" name="Summary">
     <desc><p>
	In summary I can say that the scope was a good buy. It has lots of features my old scope does not have, and can show 
	a lot higher frequencies. 
	</p><p>
	On the other hand I am still thinking whether I should actually keep the old scope. While the new one is all electronics,
	with highly integrated FPGAs internally etc - it is basically not servicable anymore. Looking at the age of the
	old scope, I suspect that it still works when the new breaks...
     </p></desc>
  </section>

